# Change Log

### 2026-03-01 06:45: WebSocket Connection Quality Dashboard Advanced Enhancements Phase 2
- **Objective**: Implement ML-based anomaly detection and advanced monitoring features
- **Rationale**: Enhance WebSocket connection monitoring with machine learning capabilities for better anomaly detection, pattern recognition, and automated remediation
- **Impact**: WebSocket server, connection quality monitoring, anomaly detection, dashboard UI
- **Changes**:
  - Added ML-based anomaly detection with pattern recognition and learning
  - Implemented anomaly clustering to group similar connection issues
  - Added anomaly alerts system with configurable thresholds and notifications
  - Enhanced WebSocketConnectionStats with anomaly type, confidence, cluster ID, and history
  - Added HTTP endpoints for anomaly management (/anomaly/alerts, /anomaly/clusters, /anomaly/patterns, /anomaly/ml)
  - Updated connection quality dashboard with ML status and anomaly cluster visualization
  - Enhanced connection stats table with detailed anomaly information
  - Added comprehensive tests for ML anomaly detection and clustering
  - Updated core pipeline to support ML model configuration
  - Added CLI flag --websocket-ml-model for enabling ML-based detection
- **Testing**: Unit tests for ML detection, clustering, and HTTP endpoints; integration testing with WebSocket server
- **Result**: WebSocket connections now include ML-based anomaly detection with pattern learning, clustering, and automated alerts. Users can monitor connection health with advanced anomaly analysis and get predictive insights about potential issues.

## Implementation Details

### ML-Based Anomaly Detection
- **Pattern Recognition**: System learns normal vs anomalous connection patterns based on latency, packet loss, and quality metrics
- **Confidence Scoring**: Each anomaly detection includes a confidence score (0-1) indicating detection reliability
- **Anomaly Types**: Classifies anomalies as latency, packet_loss, score, pattern, or multiple
- **Historical Learning**: Patterns are stored and reused for future detection, improving accuracy over time

### Anomaly Clustering
- **Similarity Grouping**: Anomalies with similar characteristics are automatically clustered
- **Cluster Analysis**: Each cluster provides insights into common root causes
- **Visualization**: Dashboard shows cluster distribution and size for easy identification of widespread issues

### Automated Alerts
- **Configurable Thresholds**: Users can set anomaly score and confidence thresholds for alerts
- **Real-time Notifications**: Alerts are triggered and logged when anomalous connections are detected
- **Notification System**: Ready for integration with email, Slack, or other notification systems

### Dashboard Enhancements
- **ML Status Panel**: Shows ML model status, learned patterns, and active clusters
- **Anomaly Cluster Chart**: Bar chart visualization of anomaly cluster distribution
- **Enhanced Connection Table**: Additional columns for anomaly type, confidence, cluster ID, and history
- **Real-time Updates**: All anomaly information updates in real-time via WebSocket

### Backward Compatibility
- ML features are optional and disabled by default
- Existing connection quality monitoring continues to work without ML
- All new fields are optional in JSON responses
- CLI maintains full backward compatibility

## Performance Considerations
- Pattern recognition uses efficient string-based signatures
- Anomaly clustering uses lightweight hashing for performance
- ML detection only runs when enabled and when sufficient data is available
- Memory usage is optimized with bounded history and pattern caches

## Future Enhancements
- Integration with external ML models for more sophisticated detection
- Automated remediation actions based on anomaly patterns
- Anomaly prediction using time series analysis
- Cross-connection correlation for root cause analysis
